===Verb===
{{en-verb|seiz|ing}}

# {{context|transitive|lang=en}} to deliberately take hold of; to [[grab]] or [[capture]]
# {{context|transitive|lang=en}} to take advantage of (an [[opportunity]] or [[circumstance]])
# {{context|transitive|lang=en}} to take possession of (by force, law etc.)
#: ''to seize smuggled goods''
#: ''to seize a ship after libeling''
# {{context|transitive|lang=en}} to have a sudden and powerful effect upon
#: ''a panic seized the crowd''
#: ''a fever seized him''
# {{context|transitive|nautical|lang=en}} to [[bind]], [[lash]] or make [[fast]], with several turns of small rope, cord, or small line
#: ''to seize two fish-hooks back to back''
#: ''to seize or stop one rope on to another''
# {{context|transitive|obsolete|lang=en}} to [[fasten]], [[fix]]
# {{context|intransitive|lang=en}} to lay hold in [[seizure]], by hands or claws (+ {{term|on|lang=en}} or {{term|upon|lang=en}})
#: ''to seize on the neck of a horse''
#: ''The text which had seized upon his heart with such comfort and strength abode upon him for more than a year.'' (''Southey'', Bunyan, p. 21)
# {{context|intransitive|lang=en}} to have a [[seizure]]
# {{context|intransitive|lang=en}} to [[bind]] or [[lock]] in position [[immovably]]; see also '''[[seize up]]'''
#: ''Rust caused the engine to '''seize''', never to run again.''

